TY  - JOUR
AB  - Presidential address delivered at Forty-fourth Annual Meeting of the American Economic Association, Washington, D.C., December 29, 1931. The early colonists settled along the Atlantic seaboard, but after the Revolution they began to push westward across the Appalachian mountains. The physical frontier had disappeared by 1890, but there were soon disclosed new frontiers of industry, finance, and commerce, as well as cultural frontiers. Great progress has been made in the physical sciences and in technology, yet even in these fields there are many unsettled questions which remain as a challenge to man's power. Economic science has achieved great progress, and has made constructive contributions to human welfare, but the unsolved problems of today constitute another frontier. The movement is now upward rather than outward and is raising cultural as well as economic levels.
AU  - Bogart, E. L.
C1  - Full publication date: Mar., 1932
DB  - JSTOR
EP  - 9
IS  - 1
